		<div class="contentDetailBody">
<span style="text-transform:uppercase;"></span><BR>
January 28, 2008 &mdash; <div>James Moore, chair of the USC Viterbi School&rsquo;s Daniel J. Epstein Department of Industrial and Systems Engineering, was recently elected vice president and president-elect of the Transportation Science and Logistics Society (TSL).&nbsp;He is also being honored by the Orange County Engineering Council with a Pioneer Educator Award.</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div><span style="display: block;">
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" class="tableCaptionedImageLeft">
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td class="tableCaptionedImageImage"><img width="167" height="223" src="/assets/055/57453.JPG" alt="" /></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td class="tableCaptionedImageCaption">James Moore</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
</span>The twin accomplishments began with Moore&rsquo;s election to the TSL post.&nbsp;The society is one of the largest components in the Institute For Operations Research and Management Science (INFORMS), which is largest professional society in its field.</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div>With 1,600 members worldwide, TSL provides a on transportation science and logistics, with the goal to identify current and potential problems and visualize solutions.</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div>As vice president and president-elect of the society, Moore serves on TSL&rsquo;s executive committee with the president and immediate past president.</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div>&ldquo;When I was a graduate student, the Transportation Science and Logistics Society provided my introduction to the research questions that have remained of greatest interest to me,&rdquo; Moore said. &ldquo;The scholars in TSL are the best experts I know in my field. &nbsp;The opportunity serve the Society in this capacity is a surprise and an honor.&rdquo;</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div>Almost coincidentally, Moore learned that he will receive the Pioneer Educator Award from the Orange County Engineering Council.<span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div>&ldquo;Professor Moore works at the boundaries of transportation engineering, logistics, and transportation planning to solve the public and private sector transportation problems that characterize life and commerce in Southern California,&rdquo; reads part of Moore&rsquo;s upcoming citation for the award. &nbsp;&ldquo;He is an interdisciplinary engineer whose research extends seamlessly across disciplinary boundaries and institutions.&rdquo;</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div>&ldquo;This award is first and foremost a recognition of the USC Viterbi School and the Epstein ISE Department as valued educational partners in the Orange County professional engineering community,&rdquo; Moore said.&nbsp;</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div>Moore will receive the award at the OCEC&rsquo;s Honors and Awards Banquet Feb. 16, the start of National Engineers Week.</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div>--Ben Murray</div>		</div>
